<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,154,682]" box="[199,554,154,178]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1893" box="[199,554,154,178]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Lissotrachelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineonotatus">
<emphasis box="[199,554,154,178]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">Lissotrachelus ferrugineonotatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="444" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,154,682]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">
are small crickets in 
<quantity box="[791,868,154,178]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" unit="mm" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6-8mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[884,945,154,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="0.[151,250,1946,1971]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,1129,1919]" captionTargetId="figure@0.[151,1436,1027,1919]" captionTargetPageId="0" captionText="FIGURE 1 Lissotrachelus ferrugineonotatus: A, male; B, female; C, teeth of right forewing (scale bar = 100 μm); D, teeth of right forewing (scale bar = 5 μm); E, teeth of left forewing (scale bar = 5 μm)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3784189" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3784189/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A–B; 
<bibRefCitation author="Chopard, L." box="[1016,1172,154,178]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" refId="ref1037" refString="Chopard, L. (1969) Grylloidea. The fauna of India and adjacent countries. Orthoptera. Vol. 2. Baptist Mission Press, Calcutta, 421 pp." type="book" year="1969">Chopard 1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yin H. - S. &amp; Liu X. - W." box="[1184,1370,154,178]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" refId="ref1497" refString="Yin H. - S. &amp; Liu X. - W. (1995) Synopsis on the classification of Grylloidea and Gryllotalpoidea from China. Shanghai Scientific and Technological Literature, Shanghai, 237 pp." type="book" year="1995">Yin &amp; Liu, 1995</bibRefCitation>
). Living 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1893" box="[193,413,190,214]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Lissotrachelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineonotatus">
<emphasis box="[193,413,190,214]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">L. ferrugineonotatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
crickets were collected from Ruili, Yunnan. Four males and five females were kept in a plastic box with small holes (diameter: 
<quantity box="[496,573,226,250]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
, height: 
<quantity box="[665,741,226,250]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
) in the laboratory in temperature 25 degree. UltraSoundGate 116 (linked with computer) were used to recorded their songs near the box at 1600 kbps/36000 Hz sample rate. Songs were replayed for analysis using Cool Edit software. To observe the teeth structures on forewings, we removed and placed them in 100% ethyl alcohol. Prior to SEM observation, samples were placed in a Quorum K850 critical point dryer (Quorum, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,191,370,394]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">UK</collectingCountry>
) to be desiccated, and then placed on conductive tape and coated with platinum. Observations were conducted with a Hitachi E-1010 scanning electron microscope at 10kV and the figures were also taken by the same instrument.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="445" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,154,682]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">
The male was observed singing without moving or chasing females. We considered it as the calling songs rather than courtship sounds, though females were nearby. Although our ears could not hear their songs, three records of songs were detected by the device (
<figureCitation box="[410,477,514,538]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1750,1775]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,711,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1437,703,1724]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 2 Characters of songs: A, B, C, waveform of three record of songs; D, frequency spectra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3784191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3784191/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Songs consisted of stereotyped chirps with almost no variation. The rate of chirps was 
<geoCoordinate box="[151,227,550,574]" degrees="5.85" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" precision="555" value="5.85">5.85 N</geoCoordinate>
/s. Each chirp contained two pulses (only one chirps in three songs having three pulses as in 
<figureCitation box="[1214,1297,550,574]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1750,1775]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,711,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1437,703,1724]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 2 Characters of songs: A, B, C, waveform of three record of songs; D, frequency spectra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3784191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3784191/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Two pulses had 0.0279± 
<geoCoordinate box="[286,368,586,610]" degrees="0.0007" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" precision="5" value="-7.0E-4">0.0007s</geoCoordinate>
interval. The frequency peak was 25.65±0.09 kHz (
<figureCitation box="[925,1122,586,610]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1750,1775]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,711,1724]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1437,703,1724]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 2 Characters of songs: A, B, C, waveform of three record of songs; D, frequency spectra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3784191" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3784191/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">Fig. 2-A2, B2, C2</figureCitation>
, D). Different to the songs of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,292,622,646]" class="Insecta" family="Eneopterinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Eneopterinae</taxonomicName>
crickets having several peaks, only one frequency peak showed in frequency spectra and no other peak was detected in range 0-36 kHz.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3784191" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3784191" box="[151,1158,1750,1776]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3784191/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" startId="1.[151,250,1750,1775]" targetBox="[158,1430,711,1724]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1158,1750,1776]" box="[151,1158,1750,1776]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,1750,1775]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">FIGURE 2</emphasis>
Characters of songs: A, B, C, waveform of three record of songs; D, frequency spectra.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1823,2028]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,154,322]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="445" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">
Both forewings had teeth. The teeth on right forewing were larger than those on left forewing. Teeth on left forewing were closer together with each other (
<geoCoordinate box="[554,627,1859,1883]" degrees="1.25" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" precision="555" value="1.25">1.25 N</geoCoordinate>
/ 5 μm), while teeth on right forewing were not so close (1 N / 5 μm). Total 109 similar teeth arranged with except for a few teeth at either end on right forewing (
<figureCitation box="[1087,1172,1895,1919]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="0.[151,250,1946,1971]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,1129,1919]" captionTargetId="figure@0.[151,1436,1027,1919]" captionTargetPageId="0" captionText="FIGURE 1 Lissotrachelus ferrugineonotatus: A, male; B, female; C, teeth of right forewing (scale bar = 100 μm); D, teeth of right forewing (scale bar = 5 μm); E, teeth of left forewing (scale bar = 5 μm)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3784189" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3784189/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). Each tooth was thin in shape with sharp edged. These features were most similar to that found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saussure" authorityYear="1874" box="[939,1083,1931,1955]" class="Insecta" family="Trigonidiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Trigonidiinae">Trigonidiinae</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[1118,1252,1931,1955]" class="Insecta" family="Trigonidiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nemobiinae">Nemobiinae</taxonomicName>
. There is no phylogenetic study including genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1893" box="[500,656,1967,1991]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Lissotrachelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[500,656,1967,1991]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">Lissotrachelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubbell" authorityYear="1938" box="[693,852,1967,1991]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lissotrachelini">Lissotrachelini</taxonomicName>
until now. 
<bibRefCitation author="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C." box="[974,1310,1967,1991]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" pagination="1 - 230" refId="ref977" refString="Brunner von Wattenwyl, C. (1893) Revision du systeme des Orthopteres et description des especes rapportees par M. Leonardo Fea de Birmanie. Annali del Museo civico di Storia naturale di Genova, 2 (13), 1 - 230. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5121" type="journal article" year="1893">Brunner von Wattenwyl (1893)</bibRefCitation>
established genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1893" box="[220,376,2003,2027]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Lissotrachelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[220,376,2003,2027]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="444">Lissotrachelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 3 new species and considered it belonging to the ant crickets, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saussure" authorityYear="1874" box="[1094,1287,2003,2027]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmecophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Myrmecophilidae</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kirby, W. F." box="[1296,1437,2003,2027]" pageId="1" pageNumber="444" pagination="1 - 562" refId="ref1154" refString="Kirby, W. F. (1906) Orthoptera Saltatoria. Part I. (Achetidae et Phasgonuridae). A Synonymic Catalogue of Orthoptera (Orthoptera Saltatoria, Locustidae vel Acridiidae), 2, i-viii + 1 - 562" type="journal article" year="1906">Kirby (1906)</bibRefCitation>
followed this classification, but treated 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saussure" authorityYear="1874" box="[578,768,154,178]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmecophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Myrmecophilidae</taxonomicName>
as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saussure" authorityYear="1874" box="[806,999,154,178]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmecophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Myrmecophilinae">Myrmecophilinae</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Chopard, L." box="[1011,1182,154,178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" refId="ref1037" refString="Chopard, L. (1969) Grylloidea. The fauna of India and adjacent countries. Orthoptera. Vol. 2. Baptist Mission Press, Calcutta, 421 pp." type="book" year="1969">Chopard (1969)</bibRefCitation>
placing it in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saussure" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Pentacentridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pentacentridae</taxonomicName>
bsased on “the shape of the head with sloping forehead and antennae inserted beneath the middle of the face”. 
<bibRefCitation author="Yin H. - S. &amp; Liu X. - W." box="[151,344,225,250]" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" refId="ref1497" refString="Yin H. - S. &amp; Liu X. - W. (1995) Synopsis on the classification of Grylloidea and Gryllotalpoidea from China. Shanghai Scientific and Technological Literature, Shanghai, 237 pp." type="book" year="1995">Yin &amp; Liu (1995)</bibRefCitation>
considered it in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubbell" authorityYear="1938" box="[571,746,226,250]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lissotrachelinae">Lissotrachelinae</taxonomicName>
in the 
<taxonomicName box="[824,972,226,250]" class="Insecta" family="Trigonidiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Trigonidiidae</taxonomicName>
. Based on the shape of forewing teeth, we consider this genus belongs to family 
<taxonomicName box="[553,701,262,286]" class="Insecta" family="Trigonidiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Trigonidiidae</taxonomicName>
. That the second joint of tarsi flattened suggests 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1893" box="[1217,1436,262,286]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Lissotrachelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineonotatus">
<emphasis box="[1217,1232,262,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1245,1436,262,286]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="445">ferrugineonotatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may belong to 
<taxonomicName box="[310,444,298,322]" class="Insecta" family="Trigonidiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="445" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nemobiinae">Nemobiinae</taxonomicName>
. These inferences should be tested by molecular phylogenetic studies in the future.
</paragraph>
